The senior special assistant in Niger Delta affairs to the president, Senator Ita Enang, has commended President Muhammadu Buhari for the award of contract for the dualisation of Calabar-Odukpani – itu roads. In a statement he said on the approval for award of the contract at N50.2 billion at penultimate Wednesday Federal Executive Council, he expressed appreciation to the President on behalf of the people of Cross River, Akwa Ibom and Abia states, and indeed the commuting public, for what he calls the great favour to the people of South South/South East and indeed the nation. This road, Enang noted was  constructed in 1976 as single lane is now for dualization from Calabar – Odukpani in Cross River State – Itu – Ikot Ekpene in Akwa Ibom State leading to the yet to be awarded section of Ikot Ekpene (Akwa Ibom) to Aba in Abia states. threat of war in the Middle East, a major oil producing region, calmed and investors switched their attention to economic growth prospects and demand for crude. Brent crude was down 14 cents, or 0.2 per cent, at $65.23 after falling more than 4 per cent over the last two days. The US West Texas Intermediate, WTI was also down 14 cents, or 0.2 per cent, at $59.42, after dropping slightly on Thursday and plunging around 5 per cent on Wednesday. “The U.S. and Iran both appear to be trying to de-escalate bringing the region back from the brink of war and reducing the risk of a major supply disruption to oil markets,” Eurasia Group said in a note. Oil prices are below where they were before a U.S. drone strike killed a top Iranian general on January 3, with Iran responding with a ballistic missile attack on Iraqi air bases hosting U.S. forces this week that left no casualties.